SIMPLE: trust
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trust
<hw>Trust</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>trust</ets>,
<ets>trost</ets>, Icel. <ets>traust</ets> confidence, security; akin to
Dan. & Sw. <ets>tr⟦oum⟧st</ets> comfort, consolation, G.
<ets>trost</ets>, Goth. <ets>trausti</ets> a convention, covenant, and
E. <ets>true</ets>. See <er>True</er>, and cf. <er>Tryst</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Assured resting of the mind on the integrity, veracity,
justice, friendship, or other sound principle, of another person;
confidence; reliance; reliance.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧O ever-failing
<xex>trust</xex> in mortal strength!⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Most take things upon <qex>trust</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Credit given; especially, delivery of property or
merchandise in reliance upon future payment; exchange without immediate
receipt of an equivalent; <as>as, to sell or buy goods on
<ex>trust</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Assured anticipation; dependence upon something
future or contingent, as if present or actual; hope; belief.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Such <xex>trust</xex> have we through Christ.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>2 Cor.
iii. 4.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>trust</qex> was with the Eternal to be deemed⟦br⟧
Equal in strength.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is committed or intrusted to one;
something received in confidence; charge; deposit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The condition or obligation of one to whom anything
is confided; responsible charge or office.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[I] serve him truly that will put me in <qex>trust</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Reward them well, if they observe their <qex>trust</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Denham.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>That upon which confidence is reposed; ground of
reliance; hope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O Lord God, thou art my <qex>trust</qex> from my youth.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. lxxi. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An estate devised or granted in
confidence that the devisee or grantee shall convey it, or dispose of
the profits, at the will, or for the benefit, of another; an estate held
for the use of another; a confidence respecting property reposed in one
person, who is termed the <xex>trustee</xex>, for the benefit of
another, who is called the <xex>cestui que trust</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>An equitable right or interest in property distinct
from the legal ownership thereof; a use (as it existed before the
Statute of Uses); also, a property interest held by one person for the
benefit of another. Trusts are <xex>active</xex>, or <xex>special</xex>,
<xex>express</xex>, <xex>implied</xex>, <xex>constructive</xex>, etc. In
a <col><b>passive trust</b></col> the trustee simply has title to the
trust property, while its control and management are in the
beneficiary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A business organization or combination consisting of
a number of firms or corporations operating, and often united, under an
agreement creating a trust (in sense 1), esp. one formed mainly for the
purpose of regulating the supply and price of commodities, etc.; often,
opprobriously, a combination formed for the purpose of controlling or
monopolizing a trade, industry, or business, by doing acts in restraint
or trade; <as>as, a sugar <ex>trust</ex></as>. A trust may take the form
of a corporation or of a body of persons or corporations acting together
by mutual arrangement, as under a contract or a so-called gentlemen's
agreement. When it consists of corporations it may be effected by
putting a majority of their stock either in the hands of a board of
trustees (whence the name <xex>trust</xex> for the combination) or by
transferring a majority to a holding company. The advantages of a trust
are partly due to the economies made possible in carrying on a large
business, as well as the doing away with competition. In the United
States severe statutes against trusts have been passed by the Federal
government and in many States, with elaborate statutory
definitions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Confidence; belief; faith; hope;
expectation.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trust deed</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a deed
conveying property to a trustee, for some specific use.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trust
<hw>Trust</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Held in trust; <as>as, <ex>trust</ex>
property; <ex>trust</ex>money</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trust
<hw>Trust</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Trusted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Trusting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>trusten</ets>,
<ets>trosten</ets>. See <er>Trust</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To place confidence in; to rely on, to confide, or repose faith,
in; <as>as, we can not <ex>trust</ex> those who have deceived
us</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will never <qex>trust</qex> his word after.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that <qex>trusts</qex> every one without reserve will at last
be deceived.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give credence to; to believe; to
credit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Trust</qex> me, you look well.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To hope confidently; to believe; -- usually with a
phrase or infinitive clause as the object.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>trust</qex> to come unto you, and speak face to face.</q>
<rj><qau>2 John 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We <qex>trust</qex>we have a good conscience.</q> <rj><qau>Heb.
xiii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>to show confidence in a person by intrusting (him)
with something.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whom, with your power and fortune, sir, you <qex>trust</qex>,⟦br⟧
Now to suspect is vain.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To commit, as to one's care; to intrust.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Merchants were not willing to <qex>trust</qex> precious cargoes to
any custody but that of a man-of-war.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To give credit to; to sell to upon credit, or in
confidence of future payment; <as>as, merchants and manufacturers
<ex>trust</ex> their customers annually with goods</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>To risk; to venture confidently.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Beguiled] by thee⟦br⟧
to <qex>trust</qex> thee from my side.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trust</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Trust
<hw>Trust</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have trust; to be
credulous; to be won to confidence; to confide.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>More to know could not be more to <qex>trust</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be confident, as of something future; to
hope.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I will <qex>trust</qex> and not be afraid.</q> <rj><qau>Isa. xii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To sell or deliver anything in reliance upon a
promise of payment; to give credit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is happier sometimes to be cheated than not to
<qex>trust</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>To trust in</b></col>, <col><b>To trust
on</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to place confidence in,; to rely on; to
depend.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Trust in</xex> the Lord, and do good.⟦rdquo⟧
<au>Ps. xxxvii. 3.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧A priest . . . <xex>on</xex> whom we
<xex>trust</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Chaucer.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her widening streets <qex>on</qex> new foundations
<qex>trust</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <mcol><col><b>To trust to</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>To trust
unto</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to depend on; to have confidence in; to rely
on; <as>as, to <ex>trust to</ex> luck</as>.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>trusted unto</qex> the liers in wait.</q>
<rj><qau>Judges xx. 36.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Trust company</ent>⟦br⟧
